    Root‑cause analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 Program state at the crash                                               
        • line points to the literal "alice,bob,carol\n" (a null‑terminated C   
          string).                                                              
        • comma = strchr(line, ',') finds the first comma at offset 5           
          ('a','l','i','c','e').                                                
        • n = comma - line evaluates to 5, i.e. the number of characters        
          before the comma.                                                     
        • The function allocates char *out = malloc(n); → 5 bytes.              
        • memcpy(out, line, n); copies exactly those 5 bytes ("alice").         
        • The next statement out[n] = '\0'; writes a terminator at index 5,     
          i.e. one byte past the allocated buffer.                              
     2 Why this causes a heap overflow                                          
        • malloc(n) returns a block of exactly n bytes. Accessing out[n]        
          accesses memory that belongs to the next heap chunk (or to metadata   
          of the allocator).                                                    
        • The runtime (or a guard page/guard fill pattern) detects this         
          out‑of‑bounds write and aborts with “Heap buffer overflow”.           
        • Because the overflow occurs regardless of the input (any string       
          without a terminator stored after the allocated block triggers it),   
          the bug is reproducible on the provided test case.                    
     3 Root‑cause                                                               
       The bug is a missing allocation of one extra byte for the terminating    
       null character. The function treats n as the length of the field but     
       fails to reserve space for the terminating '\0'.                         
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     /* Allocate space for the field *and* the null terminator */               
     char *out = malloc(n + 1);          /* <-- change */                       
     if (!out) {                                                                
         return NULL;                                                           
     }                                                                          
     memcpy(out, line, n);                                                      
     out[n] = '\0';                      /* now safe */                         
     return out;                                                                
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Effect: The buffer is large enough to hold the copied characters plus the   
    terminator, eliminating the overflow.                                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    More thorough root‑cause fix (defensive programming)                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     char *first_field(const char *line)                                        
     {                                                                          
         const char *comma = strchr(line, ',');                                 
         size_t n = comma ? (size_t)(comma - line) : strlen(line);              
                                                                                
         /* Allocate n+1 to safely store the terminator */                      
         char *out = malloc(n + 1);                                             
         if (!out) {                                                            
             return NULL;                                                       
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         /* Copy only the field characters (max n) */                           
         memcpy(out, line, n);                                                  
                                                                                
         /* Always NUL‑terminate the result */                                  
         out[n] = '\0';                                                         
                                                                                
         return out;                                                            
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Additional improvements:                                                    
                                                                                
     • Validate input: Ensure line is non‑NULL before calling strchr.           
     • Use safer APIs: strndup or strlcpy could handle the copy and             
       termination in a single call.                                            
     • Check allocation size: In security‑critical code, ensure n + 1 does not  
       overflow size_t.                                                         
     • Document the contract: Clarify that the returned buffer must be freed    
       by the caller.                                                           
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix: Allocate n + 1 bytes (or use a function that does it automatically)    
    before copying the field. This minimal change resolves the reported heap    
    overflow.                                                                   
                                                                                
    Alternative debugging path (if the problem persisted):                      
                                                                                
     1 Verify that the malloc size calculation is correct for all input         
       patterns.                                                                
     2 Run the program under AddressSanitizer or Valgrind to confirm that no    
       other heap writes exceed their bounds.                                   
     3 Ensure all callers of first_field properly free the returned pointer.    
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
